# Documentation Policy

## Document Ownership

Each document has a single, defined purpose. Never put information in a document that belongs to a different one.

| Document | Owns |
|---|---|
| `README.md` | What the project is (2-3 sentences). Local development setup. Links to deeper docs. Nothing else. |
| `SPEC.md` | What the app does from the user's perspective. Features, flows, and UX. Zero implementation or technology details. |
| `IMPLEMENTATION_PLAN.md` | Technology choices, architecture decisions, project structure, Redux store organization, data strategies. High-level — not function-level detail. |
| `DEPLOYMENT.md` | All deployment scenarios: one-time environment setup, local dev, remote deployment to test and production. |
| `backend/README.md` | Backend-specific environment variables not covered in root docs. API endpoint reference. Backend scripts. |
| `shared/README.md` | Shared type system explanation. How to use and extend the shared types. |

## No Duplication

If information already exists in one document, it must not be repeated in another. This includes:

- Setup steps covered in `README.md` must not be repeated in `backend/README.md` or anywhere else
- Deployment steps covered in `DEPLOYMENT.md` must not be duplicated in sub-package READMEs
- Architecture covered in `IMPLEMENTATION_PLAN.md` must not be re-explained in `SPEC.md` or sub-package READMEs
- When a sub-package README needs to reference something covered above, link to the parent doc instead of restating it

## What Docs Are Not

Documents must not contain:

- **Design alternatives not taken** — do not document options that were considered and rejected
- **Bug fix history** — do not record "this field was added to fix bug X"
- **Implementation rationale** that is now settled — if a decision is made and won't be revisited, don't preserve the debate
- **Stale feature lists** — if a feature is implemented, it belongs in `SPEC.md` under Implemented; remove it from Planned

## Keeping Docs Current

- When a feature is fully implemented, move it from "Planned" to "Implemented" in `SPEC.md`
- When a planned feature's design changes substantially, update `SPEC.md` to reflect the current plan — do not preserve the old design alongside the new one
- When a document becomes redundant because its content is now covered by another document, delete it rather than leaving it to go stale
